{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638129"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:49:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:49:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17692"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17692"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10406"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77979"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10406"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17692"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63415"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10457"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24317"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24364"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77979"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with gradual hearing loss. During the examination of her auditory pathways, you consider the sequence of neural relays that process sound information from the inner ear to the cerebral cortex.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the correct sequence of brainstem nuclei in the ascending auditory pathway?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cochlear nuclei \u2192 inferior colliculus \u2192 superior olive \u2192 medial geniculate","Cochlear nuclei \u2192 superior olive \u2192 inferior colliculus \u2192 medial geniculate","Inferior colliculus \u2192 superior olive \u2192 cochlear nuclei \u2192 medial geniculate","Superior olive \u2192 cochlear nuclei \u2192 inferior colliculus \u2192 medial geniculate","Cochlear nuclei \u2192 medial geniculate \u2192 superior olive \u2192 inferior colliculus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct sequence of auditory relay stations is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecochlear nuclei \u2192 superior olive \u2192 inferior colliculus \u2192 medial geniculate\u003C/strong\u003E. Sound information from the cochlea first enters the brainstem at the cochlear nuclei in the medulla via the vestibulocochlear nerve (cranial nerve VIII).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect sequences can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECochlear nuclei \u2192 inferior colliculus \u2192 superior olive \u2192 medial geniculate\u003C/strong\u003E - This sequence incorrectly places the inferior colliculus before the superior olive in the pathway.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior olive \u2192 cochlear nuclei \u2192 inferior colliculus \u2192 medial geniculate\u003C/strong\u003E - This sequence incorrectly suggests that the superior olive receives direct input from the cochlea.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInferior colliculus \u2192 superior olive \u2192 cochlear nuclei \u2192 medial geniculate\u003C/strong\u003E - This sequence presents the pathway in a completely reversed order.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECochlear nuclei \u2192 medial geniculate \u2192 superior olive \u2192 inferior colliculus\u003C/strong\u003E - This sequence incorrectly places the medial geniculate nucleus before the brainstem relays.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFrom the cochlear nuclei, most fibres cross to the opposite side and synapse in the superior olive, which is important for sound localisation. The information then travels to the inferior colliculus in the midbrain, and finally to the medial geniculate nucleus of the thalamus before reaching the auditory cortex.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The first relay station for hearing is in the medulla, where the vestibulocochlear nerve synapses with the cochlear nuclei.","Auditory signals are processed at multiple levels including the superior olive and inferior colliculus before reaching higher centres.","The majority of ascending auditory pathways cross to the opposite side of the brain during their journey through the brainstem."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63415"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17692"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63415"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T21:33:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T21:37:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10406"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77979"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a 